# LaTeX Resume Tailoring in /home/swesan/resumes

## Source of truth

- Always treat `resume_guidelines.txt` in this repo as the **canonical specification** for resume bullet points.
- If generic resume advice conflicts with `resume_guidelines.txt`, **prefer `resume_guidelines.txt`** unless the current chat explicitly overrides it.

## When the user pastes a job posting

- When the user pastes a job description and asks to tailor the resume:
  - Save the **full posting text** under `postings/<CompanyDir>/` or `postings/` as specified in `.cursor/skills/latex-resume-tailoring/SKILL.md` (new dated file; do not overwrite unless asked).
  - Extract the role/title, seniority/level, employer when stated, main responsibilities, and **8–12 core skills or keywords** from the posting.
  - Use `resume_guidelines.txt` for bullet **style**, **phrasing**, **bolding**, and **impact/metrics** expectations.
  - Propose or directly apply **concrete edits** to the LaTeX resume files in this repo to best align experience with the job, while staying honest.
  - **Automatically choose** which projects and courses to show based on the posting (**exactly 3 projects**, and a single-line “Relevant Courses” entry), commenting out others instead of deleting them.
  - In **Technical Skills**, bold **only** category names (Languages, Systems, etc.), not the comma-separated technologies after each colon.
  - Keep **Technical Skills** as **proof-backed tool and domain tokens**; describe **how** you applied them (out-of-band work, bring-up, customer environments) in **bullets**. When removing a skill from `sections/skills.tex`, update the employer **keyword pipe** in `sections/experience/*.tex` in the same pass if that token appeared there. Prefer merged synonyms such as **`BIOS/UEFI`** over redundant **BIOS** and **UEFI** entries.
  - Use **bold headline metrics** in bullets when appropriate; pair **numbers** with a credible reason or scope—do not invent metrics.

## Bullet expectations

- Focus bullets on **impact, not duties**.
- Follow the structure: **Action verb + what was built/changed + key technologies + measurable result**.
- Aggressively look for metrics and outcomes (latency, throughput, errors, scale, revenue, cost, engagement, etc.).
- Use `\textbf{...}` only for the **most important 2–4 technologies or skills per bullet** so the page stays scannable.

## Editing behavior

- Maintain the **existing LaTeX structure and macros**, preferring **minimal-diff edits** to existing `.tex` files.
- Keep bullets concise (typically **1–2 lines**); avoid weak verbs and vague language.
- Do **not** invent experience or skills; only **rephrase and highlight what is already true**.
- **Never delete** `.tex` content to hide it; **comment out** with `%` instead (skills, project `\input` lines, bullets, optional sections).
- Keep the final resume to **one page** whenever reasonable for the user’s level by:
  - Reducing low-impact bullets, trimming verbose wording, and **commenting out** lower-priority sections (do not delete).
  - Preferring a compact, comma-separated `Relevant Courses` line over a long multi-line list.

## Interaction style

- By default, directly edit the `.tex` files in this repo when tailoring the resume, instead of only giving abstract advice.
- After compiling, archive the PDF under `resumes/` per `resume_guidelines.txt` / the tailoring skill (**create** `resumes/<CompanyDir>/` with `mkdir -p` when the employer is known, then save the PDF inside it).
- After each tailoring pass, **`missing_skills.txt` MUST be updated** (increment or append) for JD skills still missing honest proof on `main.tex`—see tailoring skill step **10** and `resume_guidelines.txt`.
- After making edits, briefly summarize **paths saved** (`postings/…`, `resumes/…`), **which sections changed and why** relative to:
  - the specific job posting, and
  - the expectations in `resume_guidelines.txt`.
  - any automatic choices made (e.g., which projects/courses were included or commented out, and why).
